The abundant hydrophilic functional groups on the surface, identified through surface analysis, provided excellent water dispersion of AIE-Cdots. We measured the UV–vis absorption and fluorescence spectra of AIE-Cdots in aqueous media (
                           Fig. S1
                        ). The AIE-Cdots exhibited absorption bands corresponding to the π–π* transition at 250 nm and broad absorption peaks assigned to n–π* transitions caused by surface states in the 300–390 nm region. Under excitation at 390 nm, the AIE-Cdots emitted blue fluorescence with a maximum emission peak at 480 nm, and the emission signal was hardly affected by the various pH changes (
                           Fig. S2
                        ). The excitation-wavelength-dependent fluorescence spectrum of AIE-Cdots (
                           Fig. S3
                        ) shows that the emission peaks are slightly red-shifted with increasing excitation wavelength.

Because TC has a high coordination affinity toward Al3+, many accessible Al3+ active sites in nanoaggregates can act as a specific position for TC detection (Fig. 5
a). Fig. S8 shows the fluorescence response of Al3+-NAs prepared with a high concentration of Al3+ (100 μM) toward various antibiotics (10 μM) and TC. While other common antibiotics, including kanamycin (KAN), ciprofloxacin (CIP), erythromycin (ERY), penicillin (PEN), and lincomycin (L), had only a slight influence on the fluorescence of Al3+-NAs, TC increased their fluorescence signals. The fluorescence enhancement of Al3+-NAs was clearly observed even when other antibiotics and TC coexisted, indicating that Al3+-NAs have excellent anti-interference ability against coexisting interfering species (Fig. 5 b and 5c). We further investigated the fluorescence response by various metal ions to evaluate the stability of TC-coordinated Al3+-NAs (TC-Al3+-NAs). The fluorescence intensities of TC-Al3+-NAs were barely affected by other metal ions with coordination modes to TC ( Fig. S9 ). This result indicates that TC is stably bound to the Al3+-NAs. As shown in Fig. 5 d, the fluorescence of Al3+-NAs exhibited good linearity (R2 = 0.98) with TC concentrations in the range of 0–10 μM along with fast response (>2 min) (Fig. 5 e). The calculated detection limit was 42 nM, which was significantly lower than the maximum residue limit specified by the European Union (EU, 225 nM) and the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA, 676 nM). The practicality of Al3+-NAs was further examined in synthetic urine and milk samples. The fluorescence signal of Al3+-NAs was gradually increased with an increase in TC concentration (0–10 μM) in both samples, showing a linear correlation in synthetic urine (R2 = 0.96) and milk samples (R2 = 0.99), respectively ( Fig. S10
).
